26
00:01:56.760 --> 00:01:59.900
Eles simplesmente seguiam e queriam ser aceitos

27
00:01:59.900 --> 00:02:02.120
e queriam fazer as coisas como sempre eram,

28
00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:03.719
assim como Adolf Eichmann.

29
00:02:03.719 --> 00:02:25.000
E aí eu trago para vocês um vídeo do Steve Jobs contando essa mesma experiência que ele viveu quando ele começou a comandar a Apple. 21. 21. Yeah. You're 21. You're a big success.

30
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:30.000
You know, you have no, you've just sort of done it by the seat of your pants.

31
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.000
You don't have any particular training in this.

32
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
How do you learn to run a company?

33
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:48.860
You know, throughout the years in business, I found something, which was I always ask

34
00:02:48.860 --> 00:02:51.599
why you do things.

35
00:02:51.599 --> 00:02:56.520
And the answers you invariably get are, oh, that's just the way it's done.

36
00:02:56.520 --> 00:02:59.240
Nobody knows why they do what they do.

37
00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:02.060
Nobody thinks about things very deeply in business.

38
00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:03.060
That's what I found.

39
00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:07.120
I'll give you an example.

40
00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:13.039
When we were building our Apple I's in the garage, we knew exactly what they cost.

41
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:22.759
When we got into a factory in the Apple II days, the accounting had this notion of a standard cost,

42
00:03:25.939 --> 00:03:29.120
where you'd kind of set a standard cost, and at the end of a quarter you'd adjust it with a variance.

43
00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:31.879
And I kept asking, well, why do we do this?

44
00:03:31.879 --> 00:03:33.840
And the answer was, well, that's just the way it's done.

45
00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:38.520
And after about six months of digging into this, what I realized was the reason you do

46
00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:43.280
it is because you don't really have good enough controls to know how much it costs, so you

47
00:03:43.280 --> 00:03:45.620
guess and then you fix your guess at the end of the quarter. And the reason you don't know how much it costs so you guess and then you fix your guess at the end of

48
00:03:45.620 --> 00:03:50.240
the quarter and the reason you don't know how much it cost is because your information systems aren't good enough

49
00:03:51.699 --> 00:03:58.699
So but nobody said it that way and so later on when we design this automated factory for Macintosh

50
00:03:58.699 --> 00:04:04.939
We were able to get rid of a lot of these antiquated concepts and know exactly what something cost to the second

51
00:04:07.599 --> 00:04:13.620
So in business a lot of things are, I call it folklore.

52
00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:17.639
They're done because they were done yesterday and the day before.

53
00:04:17.639 --> 00:04:21.839
And so what that means is if you're willing to sort of ask a lot of questions and think

54
00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:35.240
about things and work really hard, you can learn business pretty fast. It's not the hardest thing in the world. It's not rocket science. Então, depois de tudo isso que a gente discutiu,

55
00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:39.720
a conclusão é que o potencial da nossa organização,

56
00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:43.740
da sua organização, está diretamente relacionado

57
00:04:43.740 --> 00:05:25.720
ao potencial da sua liderança, das suas lideranças como um todo. FISIOS O começo, sem ele, nada acontece. Então, a gente só tem um objetivo dentro da nossa organização,

58
00:05:26.399 --> 00:05:33.220
transformar as pessoas físicas para, então, as pessoas físicas transformarem as pessoas jurídicas,

59
